I love Bonnie today. I love Bonnie everyday. She was a band girl. She hung with the guys. She talked hoarsely and loudly to get her voice scratchy until she was old enough to hold her own. I relate to all this. 

I recently listened to her on a podcast and I was struck by her warmth, generosity and poise but also by how absolutely aware she is of her fame. Up there with Etta and Aretha, I forgot how much listened to her early singer days when I was finding my sound. When I couldn’t those high Aretha notes, I went back to Bonnie. I always went back to Bonnie. Her tone is an education. 

Hearing her talk made me wonder if her warmth, generosity and poise is her age, the era she grew up in or her gobs of experience playing with so many incredible people from such a young age. A culmination of all three I’m sure. Or is it just her nature? I hear her voice and it makes me wanna heart her name with a big fat marker in a bathroom stall somewhere: Forever Bonnie. 

#bonnieraitt #thisgirllovesyou

Crosby. Seeing so many beautiful posts of this man. He touched so many people. The few times we hung at shows, we would just get to the good, deep stuff right away. One time backstage at a Snarky Puppy show him, his beautiful wife Jan and I were munching on green room treats. I was going through a very hard time in a relationship and he asked for all the details and dirt — to make his assessment! He had a lot to say. At the end of this super heavy conversation, he said “you’re born to sing. You must surround yourself with people who support that and don’t hold you back from anything. I should be dead by now and if I die tomorrow, I’m going out singing.” It was penetrating and the most beautiful slap in the face. I woke up. It was actually kind of life changing. 

Photo 1 - Croz watching me perform at @groundupfest in Miami. He told me afterwards “there are just seem people who are simply MUST sing. You are this. You must sing.” 

Photo 2 - of us all on a songwriter panel with my friends @boutwillismusic @mikemazmaher @beccastevensbsb at the festival 2 years prior. How many people do you encounter where they talk about Joni. Truly. It’s very hard to talk about your “songwriter life” when you’re sitting next this man. I’m still trying to wrap my head around how he spoke about not believing in “writer’s block”. He also said “write everything down. You’re not gonna remember it in the morning.” I will never forget this day. 

Check out “Remember My Name”, the epic doc in him. Moving, truthful, like a dagger to the heart. You will be greatly missed. Thinking of you all the time and sending your strong hugs back to you, Jan. @greatsalsa 🕊️ @jamiemargs @groundupmusicny @snarkypuppy

I was 20 when I sat in at one of my first jam sessions. It was awful. It was a New Year’s Day legendary NYC hang that started at noon and went deep into the night. All the amazing cats of NYC would come out so I was paralyzed with fear but felt I had to do it. I was actually SO paralyzed with fear that I called out “Misty”, a standard I sang EVERY weekend in a wedding band. Why did I do that. The guitar player darted his eyes my way, scoffed, and said “REALLY?!” I was so embarrassed at my very existence that I choked on the tears about to fly from my eyeballs. I was hating myself for not being brave enough to call out something Chaka related (though that probably would’ve been worse). I don’t remember much of those 4 minutes. But Buddy Miles sat a bit later and I knew I was safe. No one would remember my nonsense. Here is “Misty” in the lowest of keys while I warm up for a day at the studio while making brekky. 

Also: instrumentalists, be kind to the next generation that jumps up on stage with you. Just let her do her thing. In fact, everyone be kind. Show that love. Ok, Happy Valentine’s Day.

It’s getting worse. And worse. And worse. Assault weapons are designed to fire rounds at a greater velocity than most other firearms, and, when combined with high capacity magazines, enable a shooter to fire a devastating number of rounds during a short period of time. Veterans know the power of assault weapons firsthand, and they agree: There is no reason why regular citizens should have them.

The availability of assault weapons and large capacity magazines has fueled an alarming increase in high casualty mass shootings across the nation — this year alone, the Gun Violence Archive has already counted at least 145 mass shootings in the US. Perpetrators of many of the deadliest shootings in modern American history — including Sutherland Springs, Las Vegas, Orlando, Sandy Hook, Parkland, Buffalo, Aurora, and Uvalde — used assault weapons. There is currently no federal legislation regulating assault weapons, so it’s up to states to protect their residents from mass shootings by regulating or banning the sale and manufacture of these dangerous military weapons. Call your representatives and check out the work that nonprofit, nonpartisan organizations like @march_fourth_ are doing and get involved. And thanks to all of these veterans for their service then. And their service now.

Men with massive machine guns are not there to protect you. They are there to protect the gorillas in case poachers come in from the other side of the mountain, from the Congo. 🤯 You get kinda close, watch these beauties rumble and tumble and feel a little weird about being there at all. You’re only allowed to watch them for a few minutes but that’s all you need. You head back down and drink the warmest, most delicious beer you’ve ever had. 🇷🇼 🦍

Finallyyyy! “Big Bones” is out! 

I remember being called Big Boned as a kid. It sucked. “You’re not fat. You’re just Big Boned.” What the hell is THAT. Tell that to any girl, oooof, it will mess you up.

I was bigger and taller than the other girls so I felt I had to act smaller because I took up too much room. There were days when I wore 2-3 ballet leotards just to look “thinner”. This affects how you see yourself fitting in in the world and you’re just trying to DO YOU. This also leads you to a world of body dysmorphia and self doubt especially when entering the pop industry machine where every day was pretty much an eating disorder.

This is the story behind my new song CLENCHED FISTS. It’s unlike any other song I’ve written as I dove into my own ancestry. “Two clenched fists” popped into my head in the middle of the night and I thought about the symbolism of that visual. 

It started with my great-grandma Sarah making her way to NYC from Russia. Her CLENCHED FISTS wrapped around her suitcase to me wrapping my CLENCHED FISTS  around my microphone when I started out singing in bands in NYC. Women are weaved throughout the verses, each navigating their own story with what their CLENCHED FISTS means to them as they know it. All these women face enthusiasm, adventure and even fear as they seek out the new life that awaits them. 

This story is also told through the eyes of their mother’s traditions that were potentially passed down to them. We are all these women. Always have been and always will be. 

I started this song based off a guitar riff (which is now the female choir at the end) written by @loukboudesteijn and then brought the whole thing to life with @davidgarzamusic ⚡️

Thought about the Masterclass I was going to give on the way to Amsterdam Conservatory this morning. Lots of thoughts in my head this week. Recovering vocal cords after cyclical sinus colds circulate this city (say that 3x) is no joke for a singer. Went to see my friend, the amazing laryngologist @michaelpitmanmd who has taken such good care of me for over a decade. Watch the TV screen behind me. My cords! They are beautifully wild to watch as Mike sticks a camera down my nose. This is my first time doing a nose camera, normally I do a throat cam. Not pleasant, nope. 

Checking your cords:
I waited too long. Don’t just wait for your voice to blow out before going in. I did this in 2011. Ignored the laryngitis I got repeatedly when I had a cold and I realized I had a polyp that I was constantly singing on top of. Nooooo! I’ve done hardcore vocal management since and that puppy is gone. No surgery. “I just want vocal freedom” is the haunting repetitive script that moves into your head like a bad roommate you can’t get rid of. 

Community: 
I can’t tell you the amount of voice memos and texts I’ve had this month alone with my singer friends who were all going through it like I was. The support is tremendous so find your people and ask questions - how do I make it to the show tomorrow? What do I gargle with? How do I steam on the road? And it gives you anxiety ABOUT having more anxiety. It’s endless. I love you all, you know who you are. And thank goodness for you and getting me through it! I cherish our conversations tremendously.
